<article id=3D"content" role=3D"main">

<!-- #BeginEditable "Body" -->=20
<div class=3D"video"><a><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/style=
/video.svg" alt=3D"Video" style=3D"width:56px; height:49px;vertical-align:m=
iddle; border:none;"></a><span id=3D"video0" style=3D""></span></div>


<h1 class=3D"center">Prime Factorization</h1>=20


<h2>Prime Numbers</h2>=20

<p>A Prime Number is:</p>=20
<div class=3D"def">=20
<p class=3D"center large">A whole number above 1 that <b>cannot</b> be made=
 by multiplying smaller whole numbers.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>When it <b>can</b> be made by multiplying smaller whole numbers it is a =
<b>Composite Number</b>, like this:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/p=
rime-composite.svg" alt=3D"prime composite" height=3D"155" width=3D"532"></=
p>=20
<div class=3D"center large">2 is Prime, 3 is Prime, 4 is Composite (=3D2=C3=
=972), 5 is Prime, and so on...</div>

<p>(The first few prime numbers are: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19 and 23, and=
 we have a <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/prime_numbers.html">prime =
number chart</a> if you need more.)</p>=20


<h2>Factors</h2>=20

<p>"Factors" are the numbers you multiply together to get another number:</=
p>=20
<p class=3D"center"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/f=
actor-2x3.svg" alt=3D"factors 2x3=3D6" height=3D"70" width=3D"181"></p>=20


<h2>Prime Factorization</h2>=20

<div class=3D"center80 center">=20
<p class=3D"large"><b>Prime factorization</b> is finding <b>which prime num=
bers</b> multiply together to make the original number.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>Here are some examples:</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What are the prime factors of 12 ?</h3>=20

	<p>We start working from the smallest prime number, which is 2, so let's c=
heck:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">12 =C3=B7 2 =3D 6</p>=20
	<p>Yes, it divided exactly by 2. We have taken the first step!</p>=20
	<p>But 6 is not a prime number, so we need to go further. Let's try 2 agai=
n:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">6 =C3=B7 2 =3D 3</p>=20
	<p>Yes, that worked also. And 3 <b>is</b> a prime number, so we have the a=
nswer:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><b>12 =3D 2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 3</b></p>=20
	<p class=3D"large">As you can see, <b>every factor</b> is a <b>prime numbe=
r</b>, so the answer is right.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>It is neater to show repeated numbers using <a href=3D"https://www.maths=
isfun.com/exponent.html">exponents</a>:</p>=20
<ul>=20
	<li>Without exponents:&nbsp;<b>2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 3</b></li>=20
	<li>With exponents:&nbsp;<b>2<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 3</b></li>=20
</ul>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the prime factorization of 147 ?</h3>=20

	<p>Can we divide 147 exactly by 2?</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">147 =C3=B7 2 =3D 73=C2=BD</p>=20
	<p>No we can't. The answer should be a whole number, and <span class=3D"la=
rger">73=C2=BD</span> is not.</p>=20
	<p>Let's try the next prime number, 3:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">147 =C3=B7 3 =3D 49</p>=20
	<p>That worked, now try factoring 49.</p>=20
	<p>The next prime, 5, does not work. But 7 does, so we get:</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger">49 =C3=B7 7 =3D 7</p>=20
	<p>And that is as far as we need to go, because all the factors are prime =
numbers.</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><b>147 =3D 3 =C3=97 7 =C3=97 7<br>
=3D 3 =C3=97 7<sup>2</sup></b></p>=20
</div>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What is the prime factorization of 17 ?</h3>=20

	<p>Hang on ... <b>17 is a Prime Number</b>.</p>=20
	<p>So that is as far as we can go.</p>=20
	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"larger"><b>17 =3D 17</b></span></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Another Method</h2>=20

<p>We just did factorization by starting at the smallest prime and working =
upwards.</p>=20
<p>But sometimes it is easier to break a number down into <b>any factors</b=
> we can ... then work those factors down to primes.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: What are the prime factors of 90 ?</h3>=20

	<p>Break 90 into 9 =C3=97 10</p>=20
	<ul>=20
		<li>The prime factors of 9 are <b>3 and 3</b></li>=20
		<li>The prime factors of 10 are <b>2 and 5</b></li>=20
	</ul>=20
	<p>So the prime factors of 90 are <b>3, 3, 2 and 5</b></p>=20
	<p class=3D"center larger"><b>90 =3D 2 =C3=97 3<sup>2</sup> =C3=97 5</b></=
p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Factor Tree</h2>=20

<p>A "Factor Tree" can help: find <b>any factors</b> of the number, then th=
e factors of those numbers, and so on, until we can't factor any more.</p>=
=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: 48</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images=
/factor-tree-48.svg" alt=3D"factor tree 48 =3D 2 x 2 x 2 x 2 x 3" height=3D=
"253" width=3D"229"></p>=20
	<p><b>48 =3D 8 =C3=97 6</b>, so we write down "8" and "6" below 48</p>=20
	<p>Now we continue and factor 8 into <b>4 =C3=97 2</b></p>=20
	<p>Then 4 into <b>2 =C3=97 2</b></p>=20
	<p>And last 6 into <b>3 =C3=97 2</b></p>=20
	<div class=3D"gap"></div>

<p>We can't factor any more, so we have found the prime factors.</p>=20
<p>Which reveals <b>48 =3D 2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 2 =C3=97 3</b></p>=20
<p class=3D"center larger"><b>48 =3D 2<sup>4</sup> =C3=97 3</b></p>=20
</div>=20


<h2>Why find Prime Factors?</h2>=20

<p>A prime number can only be divided by 1 or itself, so it cannot be facto=
red any further!</p>=20
<p>Every other whole number can be broken down into prime number factors.</=
p>=20
<div class=3D"two">=20
<div class=3D"lt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/images/blo=
cks223.svg" alt=3D"blocks 2 2 3" height=3D"125" width=3D"149"></div>
<div class=3D"rt">=20
<p>It is like the Prime Numbers are the <b>basic building blocks</b> of all=
 numbers.</p>=20
</div>

</div>=20

<p>This idea can be very useful when working with big numbers, such as in C=
ryptography.</p>=20
<div class=3D"floatRt"><img src=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/images/art/sa=
ge-walks-msg.svg" alt=3D"dog carries message" height=3D"235" width=3D"319">=
</div>


<h2>Cryptography</h2>=20

<p><a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfun.com/numbers/cryptography.html">Cryptog=
raphy</a> is the study of secret codes. <b>Prime factorization</b> is impor=
tant to people who try to make (or break) secret codes based on numbers.</p=
>=20
<p>That is because factoring very large numbers is very hard, and can take =
computers a long time to do.</p>=20


<h2>Unique</h2>=20

<p>And here is another thing:</p>=20
<p class=3D"center large">There is only one (unique!) set of prime factors =
for any number.</p>=20

<div class=3D"example">=20
	<h3>Example: the prime factors of 330 are 2, 3, 5 and 11</h3>=20

	<p class=3D"center"><span class=3D"large">330 =3D 2 =C3=97 3 =C3=97 5</spa=
n><span class=3D"large"> =C3=97 11</span></p>=20
	<p>There is no other possible set of prime numbers that can be multiplied =
to make 330.</p>=20
</div>=20

<p>This idea is so important it is called the <a href=3D"https://www.mathsi=
sfun.com/numbers/fundamental-theorem-arithmetic.html">Fundamental Theorem o=
f Arithmetic</a>.</p>=20


<h2>Prime Factorization Tool</h2>=20

<p>OK, we have one more method ... use our <a href=3D"https://www.mathsisfu=
n.com/numbers/prime-factorization-tool.html">prime factorization tool</a> t=
hat can work out the prime factors for numbers up to 9007199254740991.</p>=
=20
<div class=3D"gap"></div>

